  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Pre-Assessment",
      "name": "Pre-Assessment",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": true,
      "has_lesson_plan": false,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Pre-Assessment",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-2",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 1: Introduction to Computer Systems",
      "name": "Lesson 1: Introduction to Computer Systems",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How do computer systems solve problems and impact the world around us?**\n\nIn this lesson, students will explore how computing roles and innovations address real-world challenges in various industries. Through team activities, AI simulations, and collaborative discussions, students will investigate a selected innovation, assign professional roles, and reflect on the impact of computing systems on solving industry-specific problems.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Computer Innovations and Careers activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How do computer systems solve problems and impact the world around us?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will discover how computing roles contribute to solving real-world challenges. You'll explore an industry, investigate an innovation, and work with your team to understand how different roles come together to create impactful solutions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 1: Introduction to Computer Systems",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 2: Hardware",
      "name": "Lesson 2: Hardware",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**What components are essential for a computer to work?**\n\nIn this lesson, students expand their understanding of computer hardware by exploring memory, storage, processing components, and peripherals. They apply the Input-Storage-Processing-Output (ISPO) model to understand how computers manage and process data. Through guided readings, activities, and career connections, students analyze how these hardware components and peripherals work together to support different tasks.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Hardware activity guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**What components are essential for a computer to work?**\n\nHow does a computer take in, store, and process information? In this lesson, you explore memory, storage, processing components, and peripherals to see how they fit into the ISPO model (Input, Storage, Processing, Output). You also learn how different careers rely on these components to perform their work."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 2: Hardware",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 3: Troubleshooting and Optimizing Hardware",
      "name": "Lesson 3: Troubleshooting and Optimizing Hardware",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**Why is it important to have a strategy for troubleshooting?**\n\nStudents learn how to use the computational thinking skill of decomposition along with deductive reasoning to troubleshoot a variety of real-world issues that involve computer system hardware.  Additionally, they explore how different careers might implement troubleshooting practices.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Troubleshooting Hardware Issues activity guide (one for each student)\n- Print copies of the Guess Who? Device Edition handout (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**Why is it important to have a strategy for troubleshooting?**\n\nStudents learn how to use the computational thinking skill of decomposition along with deductive reasoning to troubleshoot a variety of real-world issues that involve computer system hardware.  Additionally, they explore how different careers might implement troubleshooting practices."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 3: Troubleshooting and Optimizing Hardware",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 4: Software and Operating Systems",
      "name": "Lesson 4: Software and Operating Systems",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How does software shape the way we interact with technology every day?**\n\nThis lesson introduces students to the roles of operating systems, application software, and utility software in enabling computer functionality. Through a scavenger hunt and reflective discussions, students learn to describe the purpose of each software type and connect them to real-world scenarios and potential careers.",
        "preparation": "- Digitally distribute copies of the Scavenger Hunt Activity Guide",
        "student_overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How does software shape the way we interact with technology every day?**\n\nIn this lesson, you explore different types of software and how they work together to make computers and devices useful. Through a software scavenger hunt, you learn about operating systems that control your devices, applications that help you complete specific tasks, and utility software that keeps everything running smoothly."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 4: Software and Operating Systems",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 5: Troubleshooting and Optimizing Software",
      "name": "Lesson 5: Troubleshooting and Optimizing Software",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we keep our computer systems running and performing well?**\n\nIn this lesson, students interact with an app while troubleshooting real-world system issues such as crashes, errors, and performance slowdowns. The simulation randomly introduces system scenarios that require students to test and evaluate different actions to resolve the issue before resuming gameplay, reinforcing critical thinking and problem-solving skills. Then, students work in pairs to analyze real-world computer system performance scenarios and evaluate potential actions to optimize the system.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the Optimization activity guide (one for each student)\n- Print copies of the Troubleshooting and Optimizing Software Unit Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "**How can we keep our computer systems running and performing well?**\n\nIn this lesson, you play with an app and sometimes, your system will encounter issues like crashes, errors, or slow performance, and it’s up to you to figure out how to fix the problem by testing different actions so the game can continue. Next, you work with a partner, explore options in a simulation, and use a chatbot to help make informed decisions to optimize the system."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 5: Troubleshooting and Optimizing Software",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 6: Build a Computer System",
      "name": "Lesson 6: Build a Computer System",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How can we design computational systems that balance user needs, budget, and performance?**\n\nStudents will recall important hardware components needed to create a computer system. They will analyze the needs of a fictional user to plan a computer build for the user using an AI Assistant to research and select the right components.",
        "preparation": "* Print copies of the Build a Computer System activity guide (one for each pair of students)\n* Explore [**PCPartPicker.com**](http://pcpartpicker.com/) so you are familiar with how the site is set up and can support students using it to complete the activity.\n* Familiarize yourself with the process of building a PC by looking at one or more of these guides:\n   * [**Best PC builds for gaming 2025**](https://www.tomshardware.com/best-picks/best-pc-builds-gaming) from Tom's Hardware\n\n  - [**Want a Better PC? Try Building Your Own**](https://www.wired.com/story/how-to-build-a-pc/) by Wired\n\n  - [**How to Build a PC: The Ultimate Beginner's Guide**](https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/how-to-build-a-pc-the-ultimate-beginners-guide) by PCMag\n\n  - [**The TBG DIY PC Build Guides**](https://techbuyersguru.com/tbg-diy-pc-build-guides/) by the Tech Buyer's Guru\n\n",
        "student_overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How can we design computational systems that balance user needs, budget, and performance?**\n\nIn this lesson, you will analyze the needs of a fictional user to plan a computer build for the user. You will use an AI Assistant to research and select the right components."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 6: Build a Computer System",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 7: Data in Computer Systems",
      "name": "Lesson 7: Data in Computer Systems",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How do different types of data and sensors help solve real-world problems?**\n\nStudents learn about different types of data (text, audio, visual, location, environmental/biometric) and the hardware components used to collect them. They work in teams to analyze user needs, identify required data types, and determine appropriate sensors for solving real-world problems. The lesson integrates AI chatbots for brainstorming sensor ideas and culminates in a collaborative reflection.",
        "preparation": "- Plan on how to divide the classroom into six different stations\n- Gather several sticky notes\n- Print copies of the Station Activity Cards\n- Print copies of the Data in Computer Systems activity guide (one for each student)\n- Print copies of the Computer Systems and Devices Unit Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How do different types of data and sensors help solve real-world problems?**\n\nYou explore different types of data and the sensors that are used to collect them. Working in a teams, you learn to analyze user needs, identify required data types, and determine appropriate sensors for solving real-world mysteries!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 7: Data in Computer Systems",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 8: Processing Data in a System",
      "name": "Lesson 8: Processing Data in a System",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can we process data to find patterns and solve problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, students will explore how computational tasks like sorting, filtering, and aggregating can uncover patterns and solve problems using a library dataset. Students will begin with a quick hands-on activity to introduce these concepts, then apply them systematically to real-world data about library books. Through guided examples, independent practice, and reflective discussions, students will understand how computational tools make data analysis more efficient and impactful.",
        "preparation": "- Gather **index cards** (one per student) or an equivalent number of small pieces of paper.\n- Collect enough **UNO cards** for each group of 4 students to have 20–25 cards.\n    - *(Optional)* Print and cut out the provided UNO cards if physical cards aren’t available. Prepare enough for each group of four students.\n- Print copies of the Processing Library Data activity guide (one for each student).",
        "student_overview": "**How can we process data to find patterns and solve problems?**\n\nIn this lesson, you’ll explore how to process data using computational tasks like sorting, filtering, and aggregating. You’ll work with a library dataset to uncover patterns and solve challenges, learning how computers organize and analyze large amounts of information."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 8: Processing Data in a System",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 9: How AI Uses Data",
      "name": "Lesson 9: How AI Uses Data",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How can AI help us analyze data?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore how AI models process data and the role of specialized hardware in optimizing performance. They analyze an AI model, learn about different processing units, and test their capabilities in various tasks. Using their observations and research, students determine the most suitable hardware for their AI model and justify their choice.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the How AI Uses Data activity guide",
        "student_overview": "**How can AI help us analyze data?**\n\nToday, you explore how AI processes data and the role of different processors in optimizing performance. You analyze an AI model, test various processing units, and compare their effectiveness. Using research and observations, you determine the best hardware for your AI model and explain your choice. By the end of the lesson, you understand how hardware shapes AI performance and real-world applications."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 9: How AI Uses Data",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 10: IoT and Emerging Technologies",
      "name": "Lesson 10: IoT and Emerging Technologies",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**How do IoT systems transform everyday objects into “smart” devices, and what challenges arise with their use?**\n\nIn this lesson, students learn about the Internet of Things and how internet-connected devices can automate tasks, collect real-time data, and improve efficiencies. However, they also raise concerns about security, privacy, and data ownership.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of The Internet of Things activity guide (one for each student)\n- Print copies of The Transmission of Data Unit Guide (one for each student)\n- Have sticky notes or small pieces of paper on hand for the Sticky Note Swap discussion protocol presented in the Warm-up",
        "student_overview": "**How do IoT systems transform everyday objects into “smart” devices, and what challenges arise with their use?**\n\nLearn about the Internet of Things— the ways that simple devices all around us are powering up, getting connected to larger networks, and making our lives more interesting and efficient. While these innovations hold promise, they also contain both security and privacy implications that can’t be overlooked."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 10: IoT and Emerging Technologies",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 11: User Testing",
      "name": "Lesson 11: User Testing",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How can user testing help make a product better? What happens when user testing is skipped?**\n\nIn this lesson, students explore the importance of user testing through hands-on activities analyzing real feedback data and making product development decisions. Students learn to leverage AI tools to process user testing data and practice justifying decisions about next steps based on testing insights, emphasizing the value of diverse perspectives in the development process.",
        "preparation": "- Print copies of the User Testing activity guide (one for each student)\n- Print copies of the User Testing Unit Guide (one for each student)",
        "student_overview": "<i class=\"fa-solid fa-user-graduate\"></i> ***Career Journeys***\n\n**How can user testing help make a product better? What happens when user testing is skipped?**\n\nDiscover how user testing helps create better products by analyzing real feedback and using AI tools to find patterns in user data. Work with your classmates to make and justify decisions about product improvements, learning how different perspectives can lead to better solutions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 11: User Testing",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 12: Just Because We Can, Should We?",
      "name": "Lesson 12: Just Because We Can, Should We?",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "**What are the decisions made for us without us?**\n\nIn this activity, students will engage with several different scenarios in which different ethical approaches to AI and computing systems might exist. Students will examine these scenarios from the perspective different stakeholders, ultimately using this experience in empathy to craft ethical guidelines for AI and emerging technologies.",
        "preparation": "- Make an editable copy of the [AI and Emerging Technology Slide template](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Akl28SCAO4jirah8PNAh_CpiHVemESY5UBbhFLN_KLc/edit?usp=sharing) for each group of 3-4 students\n- Preview the scenarios and decide if you will assign groups to scenarios or let groups self-select which scenario to work on\n- Print (or digitally distribute) a copy of the Ethical Guideline Activity Guide for each student",
        "student_overview": "**What are the decisions made for us without us?**\n\nYou will take be asked to role play several different personas throughout today’s activity, trying to create a set of ethical guidelines for AI and emerging technologies. By examining how these technologies manifest in real-world scenarios, you will be asked to construct your own personal guidelines and expectations."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 12: Just Because We Can, Should We?",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-3",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Lesson 13: Sustainable Systems Project",
      "name": "Lesson 13: Sustainable Systems Project",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "assessment": true,
        "overview": "**How can we design a computer system to solve a real world problem?**\n\nStudents propose and design an AI-infused computer system and demonstrate how it would contribute to achieving one of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals.",
        "preparation": "- Print out a digitally distribute a copy of the Project Guide for each student\n- Digitally distribute a copy of the System Diagram template to each group\n- Print out a copy of the System Diagram Checklist for each group",
        "student_overview": "**How can we design a computer system to solve a real world problem?**\n\nIn this project, you will brainstorm and design an AI-infused computer system that contribute to achieving one of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Lesson 13: Sustainable Systems Project",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-4",
        "script.name": "aif3-v2-2025"
      }
    },
