  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "7bf458a7-7a33-4cdd-9306-17fa5c46c5e1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Pre-Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7bf458a7-7a33-4cdd-9306-17fa5c46c5e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d8517eae-3bd5-4d30-87b0-301478e2c243"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "18a752b6-7dff-4e96-a9a5-ae25248637f7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student their own copy of the AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide. Students will use this resource throughout the unit.\n\n\n <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *computer system*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss**: *What are some examples of computing systems you use in everyday life?*\n- Use Think-Pair-Share to facilitate this discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Computer systems are everywhere in daily life, from smartphones and gaming consoles to self-checkout kiosks, smart home devices, and even AI-powered cars. This discussion helps students recognize how these systems process and respond to data in different ways. (e.g. *\"A smartwatch is a computer system because it tracks my steps and syncs data to my phone.\"*)",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to come up with examples, prompt them with real-world scenarios:\n* *\"Think about something you use daily that connects to the Internet or processes data.\"*\n* *\"Have you used self-checkout at a store? That’s a computer system!\"*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "18a752b6-7dff-4e96-a9a5-ae25248637f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3edf612b-f713-401c-ae81-6f565bb935f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e1c4f4a2-2a2d-4aed-b2f9-24765f875636",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Computer Innovations and Careers activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e1c4f4a2-2a2d-4aed-b2f9-24765f875636",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3edf612b-f713-401c-ae81-6f565bb935f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5dc03843-4ccc-4ec9-9f8e-19ca56bf9782",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Before you start exploring, let’s make sure we’re clear on two words you’ll see a lot:\n* An **industry** is a field of work, like healthcare, education, or agriculture.\n* An **innovation** is a new idea or technology that improves how that work is done.\n\nFor example, in the healthcare *industry*, smart prosthetics are an *innovation* that helps people regain mobility.\n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5dc03843-4ccc-4ec9-9f8e-19ca56bf9782",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3edf612b-f713-401c-ae81-6f565bb935f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "976bfea2-3e31-496f-966f-df304d37ef58",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s explore how computing drives computing innovation in different industries worldwide. In groups, you'll examine the computing innovation map and choose an innovation to investigate. Be prepared to share your findings!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "976bfea2-3e31-496f-966f-df304d37ef58",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3edf612b-f713-401c-ae81-6f565bb935f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62d00ed0-eddc-4b54-8ad6-b03ee693ae91",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 1. Students should open the Computer Innovation Map, and click on the markers to explore innovations in medicine, agriculture, education, and fashion. The markers have videos and descriptions to learn about each innovation. Students should select one innovation to investigate, then complete the first page of their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Pick an Innovation",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If your students are unable to access the resource linked on the level due to school network restrictions, you can have students use [this resource](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/11_vTxAX7WZTmFqn2jQRvDkErAhHlQriLj2KfWEJM2Zg/edit?usp=sharing) which contains the same information."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62d00ed0-eddc-4b54-8ad6-b03ee693ae91",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3edf612b-f713-401c-ae81-6f565bb935f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1fb08c7-b538-46d0-a181-b272ddce401c",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1fb08c7-b538-46d0-a181-b272ddce401c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3edf612b-f713-401c-ae81-6f565bb935f5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1ece9f0a-961a-494f-b257-f86784d5105b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Innovations exist to solve real-world problems for people in different industries. To truly understand your chosen innovation, you’ll interview professionals in that field. Learn about their work, the challenges they face, and how computing helps them. This will help you see why your innovation is important and how it’s making their job easier, faster, or more effective. Remember, innovation starts with people—it’s *their* needs that drive new ideas.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Exploring Innovations",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1ece9f0a-961a-494f-b257-f86784d5105b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c76c81f9-b0aa-4023-b6b2-00ebe4cbbab0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students use the table on the slide to pick which level they should go to next. Levels 2 through 9 have several industry professionals they can interview in different industries. Student should choose the level that matches their selected innovation and complete the Industry Interviews section of their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Industry Interviews",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You may choose to demo how to interact with AI Chat before sending students off to conduct these interviews on their own."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c76c81f9-b0aa-4023-b6b2-00ebe4cbbab0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a8062b97-32eb-40b5-9679-430b712b988a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "So far, you’ve explored how industry professionals use computing innovations and the challenges they face. Now, let’s shift to the technical roles—the engineers, developers, and designers who build and refine these innovations. These experts work closely with industry professionals to gather feedback, test solutions, and ensure the technology meets real-world needs. Next, you’ll watch career videos to learn about these roles, then conduct an AI interview with a professional to understand their impact on innovation.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Defining Roles and Developing Innovations",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a8062b97-32eb-40b5-9679-430b712b988a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e3d4b76a-c5ee-490b-9789-7f3724fb6702",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students each choose one of the roles (Hardware Engineer, Software Engineer, Product Designer) within their group - each group should have only one person serving that role.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 10. Each student selects the option with their assigned technical role. They watch a short video to introduce them to the skills and responsibilities for their selected role.",
        "progression_name": "Exploring Technical Roles"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e3d4b76a-c5ee-490b-9789-7f3724fb6702",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41b880df-f0a6-441f-bd13-c053796035a2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Students will share their observations about the career they explored in a whole class discussion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What stood out to you about the career you explored?*\n- **Round Robin Sharing**: Invite students to share one insight about their chosen career. If time allows, go around the room or ask for volunteers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion aims to encourage students to reflect on the skills and tools used in different computing careers and to connect these insights to their own interests. (e.g., *\"I didn’t realize product designers help decide how apps and websites look and feel!\"*).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 11. Student use AI chat to research how their assigned role contributes to building their selected innovation and record their findings on page 3 their activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Your Role in Innovation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41b880df-f0a6-441f-bd13-c053796035a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c3838f2-7b91-4e42-b2a4-61a259c26145",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** In their groups, students take turns sharing how their role contributes to building their selected innovation and record notes in the Your Role in Innovation section of their activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c3838f2-7b91-4e42-b2a4-61a259c26145",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f2b5166a-d3f4-4cad-a4fa-8dffeaa6946f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Computer Innovations and Careers Activity Guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f2b5166a-d3f4-4cad-a4fa-8dffeaa6946f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "771ef2f6-2b47-4214-af50-bf9548ff147e",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Pair student groups with another student group (ideally one with a different selected innovation) to share their findings.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 12 to complete the reflection questions.",
        "progression_name": "Check For Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The reflection questions on Level 12 can be used to assess students' understanding of different career pathways in computing and how computer systems and people work together to solve problems."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "771ef2f6-2b47-4214-af50-bf9548ff147e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "318cc3cb-1460-484f-bbc1-b3a10e372afd"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "058cfbe7-42c2-4e35-ae68-7ac9f63fe0c3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "058cfbe7-42c2-4e35-ae68-7ac9f63fe0c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a28ff300-1322-48c4-85f0-901a2a77d10b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0ad6d5f8-8cde-46e0-b369-db8a038854fb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define *hardware*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0ad6d5f8-8cde-46e0-b369-db8a038854fb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fbb9a4a1-09a7-46af-98d5-718062535a3a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "228fbad2-f59a-497d-8510-93d1edb4aee2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The most noticeable hardware devices are input and output devices, also known as peripherals.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "228fbad2-f59a-497d-8510-93d1edb4aee2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fbb9a4a1-09a7-46af-98d5-718062535a3a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f12d5358-23c9-4985-90d9-8b073e5cf31a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define *input devices* and *output devices*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Hardware activity guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f12d5358-23c9-4985-90d9-8b073e5cf31a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fbb9a4a1-09a7-46af-98d5-718062535a3a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5cdc5ee7-2835-4d0b-bce9-2d572e5398ca",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": " Input and output devices are all around us—they’re how we interact with and receive information from computer systems every day. Now, let’s take a closer look at different devices. \n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5cdc5ee7-2835-4d0b-bce9-2d572e5398ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fbb9a4a1-09a7-46af-98d5-718062535a3a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "557d9de9-c074-49c0-b93e-4ec314201627",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students look at each image, guess what it is and then determine if it’s an input or output device. Once they know what the item is and whether it’s an input or output device, have them write it in the Venn diagram below in their activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Students will discuss the essential components a computer needs to function beyond input and output devices.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show the zoomed in image on screen and give students 30 seconds to figure out what it is. Have students share out what they think the image is.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students talk with their partner to decide if this is input, output, or both. Have them write down the item in the corresponding category in the Venn Diagram. Explain that speakers are an example of output, they produce sound that the hardware user can hear.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show the zoomed in image on screen and give students 30 seconds to figure out what it is. Have students share out what they think the image is.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students talk with their partner to decide if this is input, output, or both. Have them write down the item in the corresponding category in the Venn Diagram. Explain that a controller is example of input, they have buttons that the user can press to control different things.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show the zoomed in image on screen and give students 30 seconds to figure out what it is. Have students share out what they think the image is.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students talk with their partner to decide if this is input, output, or both. Have them write down the item in the corresponding category in the Venn Diagram. Then have them fill out the Venn Diagram with any other input and output devices they can think of. Explain that a headset is an example of both input and output, they produce sound that the hardware user can hear and have a microphone to capture the user speaking.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  *Besides input and output devices, what other components does a computer need to work?*\n- Round Robin Sharing: Invite students to share one insight about a crucial internal component that makes a computer function (e.g., CPU, RAM, storage, power supply). If time allows, go around the room or ask for volunteers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion aims to help students recognize that a computer is more than just peripherals—it requires processing power, memory, and storage to operate. By identifying these key components, students will build a foundation for understanding how computers process and store information.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "557d9de9-c074-49c0-b93e-4ec314201627",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fbb9a4a1-09a7-46af-98d5-718062535a3a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "499264f7-4f97-43b0-9b48-d8b77d86e036",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "So far, we’ve learned about input and output devices—these are the parts of a computer that let us interact with it. But computers do more than just take in and display information. They also need to store dataand process it before sending the results to an output device. All computers, from smartphones to supercomputers, follow a basic cycle called the ISPO Model—which stands for Input, Storage, Process, and Output. Let’s watch a short video that explains these four key components in more detail.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Hardware Components",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "499264f7-4f97-43b0-9b48-d8b77d86e036",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1ced5ec2-71e3-4a77-90b5-ab100534e9fb",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"How Computers Work\" from timemarks 2:50 to 4:24 to learn about the ISPO model."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1ced5ec2-71e3-4a77-90b5-ab100534e9fb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7d3df5cd-4f5a-4ca0-983d-b2d9e83dafd9",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Computers rely on storage to manage data efficiently.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7d3df5cd-4f5a-4ca0-983d-b2d9e83dafd9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a4df0b0-3cb0-4729-b397-9f443c2396c8",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define *storage*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a4df0b0-3cb0-4729-b397-9f443c2396c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "98ef7f1a-1e7d-4c01-9aa2-3545284792c0",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s take a look at actual storage components. These components play a crucial role in how a computer accesses and saves information. Everything from opening a file to loading a game depends on memory and storage working together. In this activity, you'll explore these components and complete the analogy to explain their roles.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "98ef7f1a-1e7d-4c01-9aa2-3545284792c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b5c42738-ba94-4350-9507-648453d7bedc",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 1. Each student will read about storage components and take notes by by matching the phrase in the word bank to the correct analogy for each in the Storage section of their activity guide. Have students complete the Storage rows in their Unit Guide by providing at least one example of each.",
        "progression_name": "Storage Components"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b5c42738-ba94-4350-9507-648453d7bedc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7ed85ef8-270a-4dd7-9cc2-640e4fd405f1",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we've talked about storage, let's move on to another critical part of a computer—processing components.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7ed85ef8-270a-4dd7-9cc2-640e4fd405f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fcb6451a-f8d7-4b69-a30c-8c2305cd5e06",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define *processing components*."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fcb6451a-f8d7-4b69-a30c-8c2305cd5e06",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "acd96b08-d5e0-4967-a2e1-ef2794c5ca0b",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Everything from opening an app to playing a video game relies on processing power. In this activity, you’ll learn more about these components and complete the analogy to explain their role.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "acd96b08-d5e0-4967-a2e1-ef2794c5ca0b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0c0a2c6c-7a71-4721-959f-98940772e97c",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 2. Each student will read about processing components and take notes by matching the phrase in the word bank to the correct analogy for each in the Processing Components section of their activity guide. Have students complete the Processing Components in their Unit Guide by providing at least one example of each.",
        "progression_name": "Processing Components",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Hardware Activity Guide can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0c0a2c6c-7a71-4721-959f-98940772e97c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f191582-c13f-4ebd-bcc8-9ec345c4d4dc",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we’ve explored individual computer components, let’s see how they all come together to make a functioning system. In this activity, you’ll be matching the descriptions of each component to the names and pictures by dragging and dropping. As you do this, think about how these components interact and depend on one another.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f191582-c13f-4ebd-bcc8-9ec345c4d4dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e43b51c7-923d-415a-b295-e93584d2c343",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 3. Each student will open the PC Builder and drag and drop component descriptions from the left panel into the diagram, placing them in their correct locations. They will then select a highlight color to categorize each component based on its role in the computer system.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Once students have had some time to complete their work, have them compare their work with others to answer any questions they might have or to discuss any differences in how they labeled their diagram.\n",
        "progression_name": "Connecting Components"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e43b51c7-923d-415a-b295-e93584d2c343",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "77f1077c-66b3-45fb-9b61-68f63a310b0d",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Use the “Self Check” slide to have students check their work against the key. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Adding to the Unit Guide -** You may choose to have students take a screenshot of their PC Builder slide and add it to their Unit Guides as a reference for them to use throughout the rest of the unit."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "77f1077c-66b3-45fb-9b61-68f63a310b0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6cab3e09-e726-4ae8-8b03-e618d7008eec",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you’ve built a computer, let’s explore how different professionals rely on specific components for their work. Whether it's gaming, music production, content creation, or graphic design, each of these fields depends on certain hardware components to get the best performance. In this next activity, you'll choose a career perspective, watch a video from an expert in that field, and reflect on the role of a key component like the GPU, CPU, SSD, or RAM.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Career Hardware Needs",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6cab3e09-e726-4ae8-8b03-e618d7008eec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc1f5e77-4a92-48e8-8fc0-b30b2ad2c360",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 2, Level 4 to complete Levels 4 and 5. Each student will select a career option—gamer, music producer, content creator, or graphic designer. They will watch a short video where the professional explains how a specific hardware component (GPU, CPU, SSD, or RAM) impacts their work.",
        "progression_name": "Career Hardware Needs",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use responses to this reflection question to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dc1f5e77-4a92-48e8-8fc0-b30b2ad2c360",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3a3b2d7-8ebc-4c78-b276-6791263ffb75"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d42ccbe3-8f21-4d64-aaab-09e092ab97e6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Have students respond to the Question of the Day in their Unit Guides. After students have had some time to respond, assign students numbers in small groups and give them a discussion prompt. After a short discussion, randomly call out a number—students with that number share their group’s response.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Teaching Tip\nIf you have time and want to give students an example of how all these components might fit together in a real computer, you may choose to show them this video [\"Build My First PC\"](https://youtu.be/QlaTC0yGoPg?si=bR2eA1MQrYS5iMZR) or any other you find via a web search."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d42ccbe3-8f21-4d64-aaab-09e092ab97e6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "07f2e561-a17b-4b1c-9d4a-36725fbb1122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f7a239a4-ef02-4971-846a-9d9ac52973c0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Student responses to the Question of the Day in the Unit Guide can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f7a239a4-ef02-4971-846a-9d9ac52973c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "07f2e561-a17b-4b1c-9d4a-36725fbb1122"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1e37890-766f-484e-9eda-7c3a2f926218",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Guess Who? Device Edition handout.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write one to two **yes** or **no** questions with a shoulder partner that can help to narrow down the possible devices (*e.g. Does the device have a touch screen?*)\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Call on students and have them pose one of their questions to ask out loud. You should answer with a ***Yes*** or ***No*** depending which device you’ve chosen. Instruct students to cross out the options they think are eliminated based on your answer on their activity guides. Continue this until students the majority of students raise their hand, signaling that are able to use deductive reasoning in order to accurately guess the device.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What strategy did you use to determine the device?*\n- *How could you have arrived at the correct device quicker?*\n- **Stop & Jot**: Students quickly write a short response to the prompt before continuing the discussion\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students might have asked about specific properties – the use, the appearance, or the price, for instance. By asking enough of these questions, they are able to systematically eliminate possibilities until only one remains. This is an example of deductive reasoning and is a useful troubleshooting strategy that we will use in today's lesson. Students might note that asking the questions in a different order might have helped them narrow down the potential right answer more quickly depending on which question they asked first. Asking a question that might eliminate the most possible answers is an effective strategy to employ.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1e37890-766f-484e-9eda-7c3a2f926218",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c460109a-07a2-4d03-b3f4-d21e29ed2ff4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f414e12-13af-44a7-83ef-93f7d730a292",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today you’re stepping into the shoes of a tech professional—like an IT technician, hardware engineer, or systems support specialist. These professionals use logical thinking and problem-solving every day to diagnose and fix real hardware issues. Let's see how you'd approach it.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f414e12-13af-44a7-83ef-93f7d730a292",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c460109a-07a2-4d03-b3f4-d21e29ed2ff4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "928f42bf-c957-4d57-a283-8a34eba2b1f5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *troubleshooting*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the SNOT troubleshooting strategy and the first step.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the second step of the SNOT strategy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the third step of the SNOT strategy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the last step of the SNOT strategy.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Troubleshooting Hardware Issues activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Students should navigate to Lesson 3, Level 1.",
        "name": "Troubleshooting Hardware Issues",
        "progression_name": "Wearable Troubleshooting Scenario"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "928f42bf-c957-4d57-a283-8a34eba2b1f5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2febd1f3-5a32-478e-b03e-f8ebca0360c8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Ask a student read the description of the issue in the first panel, then have students examine the diagram on the right-hand side. This diagram is an abstraction of a computing system with descriptions of the important hardware components and connections. Students should restate the issue that the user in their own words under the ***Self*** step on page one of their activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** With a partner, students should examine the possible technical solutions to Maya's issue with her wearable on the second panel of Level 1. Have them select the most likely solutions and write them in the boxes under the ***Neighbor*** portion of their activity guide. Encourage students to also add a few of their own ideas into the activity guide as well.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students should examine the online resources presented on the remaining panels on Level 1 to narrow down Maya's problem further. In their activity guide, have them cross out solutions that seem unlikely given the new information that they learn from these online resources.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "From these online resources, students should realize that the issue seems to be centered around either the ***power level*** or ***storage capacity***, so they should be able to eliminate options that aren’t related to either of these categories. Model this for students for this scenario if you feel like your students would benefit from understanding how to use deductive reasoning to eliminate options they may have written down on their activity guides. Remind them about how this process is similar to the Guess Who? Warm-up activity."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2febd1f3-5a32-478e-b03e-f8ebca0360c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "953a68c1-40cc-431d-8e98-b922646ede06",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "953a68c1-40cc-431d-8e98-b922646ede06",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "baa0a184-ce00-420f-9d56-31810e45c2a7",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We’ve already brainstormed possible reasons why Maya’s fitness tracker isn’t working. Now, let’s use those ideas to ask her questions that help us eliminate incorrect causes and find the real issue! Our goal is to rule out possibilities one by one until we find the most likely cause. In this case, you will be acting as the Technical Expert to assist Maya while an AI will be acting as Maya.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "baa0a184-ce00-420f-9d56-31810e45c2a7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5579f6aa-ae41-4bb1-a47f-622da2440d48",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 2. Guide students through troubleshooting Maya’s wearable as a class:\n- Use this [**example script**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1EYYl4pCvx9htfz1RpXylU3SZpaUf_K_dlkUNeNPZMmQ/edit?usp=sharing) for the demo.\n- Model how to ask logical questions to gather information and eliminate incorrect causes.\n- Reference the activity guide to pull information from self, a neighbor, and online resources.\n- Show how to use deductive reasoning to propose and test a solution.",
        "progression_name": "Troubleshooting Maya's Wearable"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5579f6aa-ae41-4bb1-a47f-622da2440d48",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e26460ab-9dba-4722-97bb-9b1de392f89a",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Before students begin their own troubleshooting chats, model one live as a class using a character like Maya. Walk through how to ask a clear question, read the AI’s response carefully, and use it to eliminate unlikely causes. This helps students think critically instead of guessing. Remind them that this process is similar to the Guess Who? warm-up. Each question narrows the list of possibilities."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e26460ab-9dba-4722-97bb-9b1de392f89a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7adc0460-963b-44d8-a0ce-27d014e35f87",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 3 to complete the **You Do** section of the activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Hardware Troubleshooting Scenarios"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7adc0460-963b-44d8-a0ce-27d014e35f87",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "40eefaed-07b4-4194-9770-3ef4a4ab8a11",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Assist students as necessary with the steps of the SNOT strategy."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "40eefaed-07b4-4194-9770-3ef4a4ab8a11",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "03e0512e-b47c-4a08-889b-df587fa2cccf",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Next, you will assume the role of the technical expert, acting like an IT support agent. Ask questions, investigate potential causes, and use available resources to find the most logical solution.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "03e0512e-b47c-4a08-889b-df587fa2cccf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0ebc8788-c022-40ad-aaee-f04f77308f79",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 4. Students act as tech support for a user experiencing the same issue in the AI Chatbot simulation. They should complete their activity guide for the scenario that they have chosen, identifying the most likely cause of the problem.",
        "progression_name": "Tech Support Chatbot",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Troubleshooting Hardware Issues Activity Guide can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0ebc8788-c022-40ad-aaee-f04f77308f79",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6911420b-8eb6-4724-afc5-533867cecf89",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did employing a strategy for troubleshooting assist with resolving hardware issues?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students might articulate that using a strategy like SNOT reduces guesswork and frustration by breaking down the problem into manageable parts (**decomposition** in computational thinking), helps pinpoint causes more quickly and accurately, and encourages independent, logical problem-solving skills that transfer to various real-world situations.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *decomposition*.\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Hardware Careers: Components and Troubleshooting"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6911420b-8eb6-4724-afc5-533867cecf89",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8e463768-fcca-4714-9829-819b416fe4e1",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Mastering a troubleshooting strategy is important across a range of careers, especially those that deal with hardware. Let's take a look at a couple of those careers now and think about how those professionals might incorporate troubleshooting in their daily workflow.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8e463768-fcca-4714-9829-819b416fe4e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b9693910-eb8d-4ddc-b3f8-58d0a010933e",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 3, Level 5 to complete Levels 5 and 6.\n- **Level 5:** Students choose one of the videos that provides details about a hardware-related career\n- **Level 6:** Students speculate about how troubleshooting strategies might be employed within this specific career",
        "progression_name": "Hardware Careers: Components and Troubleshooting",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The free response questions on Level 6 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b9693910-eb8d-4ddc-b3f8-58d0a010933e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c86e1caf-aea2-46a6-95e3-6554e08619c5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e8ef38e-b20c-49a4-8d44-178989540a32",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e8ef38e-b20c-49a4-8d44-178989540a32",
        "lesson_activity.key": "12f35c2d-5ac9-4666-973d-2e4309194aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a763df47-50a7-4de9-a215-ff901e7c69ad",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Different devices are built with different hardware. Some have bigger screens, some have better cameras. They also run different software and operating systems, which can change what they are best suited for. In this activity, you’ll compare devices to see which works best for a given scenario.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a763df47-50a7-4de9-a215-ff901e7c69ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ca178a40-f68f-4808-9acf-019dcca46329"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0bc74bca-8379-456d-aed1-319355f20827",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to show each scenario and ask students which device they would use for that scenario. Ask students to hold up one finger if they would choose laptop, two fingers if they would choose a phone, or three fingers for a tablet. Have students look around the room to see if their answer is different from their peers. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  _Which device would be easiest to complete the task? Why?_\n* **Popcorn Share**: Ask a question and have students respond one at a time, “popping” in when they have something to share. Continue until a variety of ideas are heard.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to recognize that tasks that require a lot of typing or a bigger screen are more easily done with a computer (or a tablet with an external keyboard) rather than done on a phone. Tasks that require a high quality camera or are time-dependent are more easily done on a phone. Tasks that mimic using a paper and pencil are best suited for a tablet with an external stylus. Students might find that choosing a device for some of the tasks, such as editing a video, are a matter of personal preference.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0bc74bca-8379-456d-aed1-319355f20827",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ca178a40-f68f-4808-9acf-019dcca46329"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d3ccd3cc-a182-4924-bdc0-83b9235ed039",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video \"How Computers Work: Hardware and Software\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Questions To Consider with the **Video:** \n- *What pieces of hardware do you recognize?*\n- *How are operating systems different from other types of software?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize the CPU and also various input and output components in the video. They may also point out that in the video “Memory” has a generic label but that this job would be taken care of by a hard drive or RAM. Listen for students to rephrase “master program” from the video in their own words or articulate that it controls which software runs and which input and output devices it has access to.",
        "name": "Software Scavenger Hunt",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d3ccd3cc-a182-4924-bdc0-83b9235ed039",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf120f47-2c3f-4a62-b152-7c5aa2879597",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cf120f47-2c3f-4a62-b152-7c5aa2879597",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e21e8bc-883b-4fc8-8ac8-a6bfb36deec5",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Software and hardware are like a team. The hardware performs the physical tasks—like displaying images on the screen, printing a document, or saving files on a hard drive. But it’s the software that decides what to display, print, or save and how to do it.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e21e8bc-883b-4fc8-8ac8-a6bfb36deec5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7bb7a01a-0fec-4e85-acd6-9cf6531a29c4",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7bb7a01a-0fec-4e85-acd6-9cf6531a29c4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "622232f5-da9d-4d7d-b72e-baa767c30020",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "622232f5-da9d-4d7d-b72e-baa767c30020",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "069f0e5e-e185-41ab-834a-5f2986ec214a",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "069f0e5e-e185-41ab-834a-5f2986ec214a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f1fec09e-51f0-4f87-9608-006a5ba9228c",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the components of a computer system diagram.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Click through the animated slide to introduce operating systems, application software, and utility software.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Show students the Content Creator slide and read the quote. Have students discuss with a partner which software type is most important in this role and why. Call on a student to explain their answer. Click through the animated slide to reveal the answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Show students the IT Specialist slide and read the quote. Have students discuss with a partner which software type is most important in this role and why. Call on a student to explain their answer. Click through the animated slide to reveal the answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Show students the iOS Developer slide and read the quote. Have students discuss with a partner which software type is most important in this role and why. Call on a student to explain their answer. Click through the animated slide to reveal the answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have each pair make a copy of the Scavenger Hunt slides. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work on the Scavenger Hunt. Have them take screenshots of their own devices or have them screenshot the Computer Simulator slides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students are working encourage them to share task solutions with each other as they explore where to find these. Push them to consider looking in multiple places and on different devices for the tasks they might get stuck on. They don’t need to find all the solutions on a single device or platform. If students finish early, push them to find as many examples for the bonus tasks as possible.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Here are some resources that can help students get unstuck if they can't get going on the scavenger hunt.\n- [Puter](https://www.loom.com/share/ae0b0be8276a44c3b8f99f294f6b049a?sid=82a38b15-d003-4dc6-8cd2-428d6f809e02)\n- [Mac and Windows](https://support.home.sophos.com/hc/en-us/articles/115005340066-Finding-Operating-System-Information-on-Windows-and-Mac)\n- [Chromebooks](https://youtu.be/8Oy6Uiix7U0?si=O2b7CFDJSL0z6v-L)"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f1fec09e-51f0-4f87-9608-006a5ba9228c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9ce4c62-c1d0-40e8-8cc7-079bafc1fa2c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 4, Level 1 to answer the questions.",
        "progression_name": "Software Scavenger Hunt Debrief",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This level is designed to use the Student Summaries feature, which lets you view and display the responses from the class. This requires having this level opened on your computer and, in the teacher panel, selecting the current section of your classes. [**Click here to learn more about viewing student responses**](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/14544890300301-Can-I-see-a-summary-of-all-my-students-responses-for-question-based-levels). If you are unable to use the student summaries, you can also run this as an unplugged discussion where students vote in their seats or move to different corners of the room depending on their responses. Ultimately, students need a way to take a stand and be ready to discuss their opinions in the next slide."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9ce4c62-c1d0-40e8-8cc7-079bafc1fa2c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "858223fb-a579-4c2f-96f8-da664b4beeaf",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "858223fb-a579-4c2f-96f8-da664b4beeaf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "daae1813-fb41-4be4-b465-ab9b562f4e16",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What did you learn about the roles of operating systems, application software, and utility software?*\n- *Which of these types of software do you use most often, and why?*\n- *How do you think understanding these tools will help you in the future?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Ensure students can clearly articulate the distinct roles of each type of software: operating systems manage hardware and software, application software helps users complete tasks, and utility software keeps systems running smoothly. Help students connect the lesson to their own lives by identifying the software they use regularly. Highlight how each type of software impacts their day-to-day activities, such as gaming, communicating, or studying. Prompt students to consider why some types of software might feel more \"invisible\" (like utility software) compared to application software they interact with directly. Discuss how knowledge of these software types applies to future careers or problem-solving scenarios (e.g., using applications in a job, troubleshooting operating systems, optimizing devices with utilities). Emphasize how understanding software roles can make students more independent when troubleshooting or choosing the right tools for a task. Help students see the value of learning about software now to prepare for challenges in technology-driven fields or daily life.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Scavenger Hunt Activity Guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives.\n\nThe free response questions on Level 1 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "daae1813-fb41-4be4-b465-ab9b562f4e16",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81814d89-60f2-4a79-8fb2-494be4678188"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f4fa3022-13f3-4102-82b3-6dc7b57b2a69",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Review the Question of the Day.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Help students articulate that software enables hardware to perform meaningful tasks and makes devices useful. Ask guiding questions like, “Can you give specific examples from the scavenger hunt that relate to your everyday lives or future careers?”. Encourage students to consider how their own devices and software enable their daily tasks and what they would do if these systems failed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Student responses to the Question of the Day in the Unit Guide can be used to formatively assess their understanding of how to choose the appropriate software and how software and hardware work together. \n\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f4fa3022-13f3-4102-82b3-6dc7b57b2a69",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d45fbdd3-5055-4f58-bb28-56cd1335e2c9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "30e2af17-fdc3-4bac-8971-a7945206f7c7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do these jobs have in common?*\n* **One Word Summary:** Ask students to choose one word that captures the essence of a topic or lesson. Have them briefly explain their choice to a partner or share with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Pull out that they all work on seeing how products work, meet certain standards, or don’t.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video \"Meet Test Engineers at Google\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Question to Consider While Watching:**\n- *Why do you think Google invests the money and resources that it does into test engineering?*\n* **Think, Pair, Share:** Prompt students with a thought-provoking question and give them time to think independently. Have them discuss with a partner, then call on pairs to share key takeaways with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to point out that catching errors and bugs will result in a better experience for users and Google’s ability to sell more products. Students may also bring up that companies can build trust in their products by investing money into testing them internally before releasing them to the public.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "30e2af17-fdc3-4bac-8971-a7945206f7c7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e106cb38-cbb1-4e25-9aa4-7159972d15f1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a8030a21-2107-48c3-a189-92419a6668a7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a8030a21-2107-48c3-a189-92419a6668a7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e106cb38-cbb1-4e25-9aa4-7159972d15f1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dd588d4f-be8e-473d-847d-2ff8b42f2f2f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dd588d4f-be8e-473d-847d-2ff8b42f2f2f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e106cb38-cbb1-4e25-9aa4-7159972d15f1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1da95065-965f-4ce6-b9b3-7fb4617fba03",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 1. Give them time to discover how it works, run across the scenarios that pop up as they are playing the game, and attempt to troubleshoot them.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Troubleshooting",
        "progression_name": "Troubleshooting",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students that they can’t break this level so encourage them to try as many things with the level as they can think of to solve the problems they encounter."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1da95065-965f-4ce6-b9b3-7fb4617fba03",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6a883090-4dbf-4e6f-a60b-655ad28c5947",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6a883090-4dbf-4e6f-a60b-655ad28c5947",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49fb58fe-931a-46a6-bc6e-3c25976184dd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 2 and have them answer the prompts.",
        "progression_name": "Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This level is designed to use the Student Summaries feature, which lets you view and display the responses from the class. This requires having this level opened on your computer and, in the teacher panel, selecting the current section of your classes. [**Click here to learn more about viewing student responses**](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/14544890300301-Can-I-see-a-summary-of-all-my-students-responses-for-question-based-levels). If you are unable to use the student summaries, you can also run this as an unplugged discussion where students vote in their seats or move to different corners of the room depending on their responses."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Student responses to the questions in Level 2 can used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49fb58fe-931a-46a6-bc6e-3c25976184dd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da85bc99-d782-466e-8c2e-d9618f882c4e",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da85bc99-d782-466e-8c2e-d9618f882c4e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "903a5396-db27-4c29-b782-ddf6a7754f8a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which scenario felt most realistic?*\n- Use the information from the student summary screen (or other class voting method) to guide the conversation. Invite a student from each area to share their rationale.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to share comparisons to real-world troubleshooting situations they’ve encountered and how those were similar or different to what they encountered in the simulation. Pull out the idea of a process being followed no matter what the problem you are facing.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is one step you would always try first in a real-world troubleshooting process?*\n- Use the information from the student summary screen (or other class voting method) to guide the conversation. Pick out themes or specific answers for students to expand on.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to share the “why” behind the step they picked and have them expand on their reasoning. Some examples of things students might share:\n- “I always restart my device when there is an issue because I’ve found that it fixes most problems even if I don’t necessarily understand why.”\n- “I start by googling the error or problem I’m facing to see if I can find a youtube video showing how to fix it. That way I have a step-by-step guide that I can go through at my own pace.”\n- “I would try anything that would help me narrow down the what it causing the issue because that’s what we learned a few lessons ago.”"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "903a5396-db27-4c29-b782-ddf6a7754f8a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "58ccc23f-4ae8-4b6a-9029-1d3d70a3fd38",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we’ve worked on troubleshooting when things aren’t working correctly, we are going to focus on solving a different type of problem: how do you make sure your computer system performs at its best for the task you are trying to accomplish? This is known as optimization.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Optimizing",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "58ccc23f-4ae8-4b6a-9029-1d3d70a3fd38",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c032207e-c253-4112-9b5d-01c549dde365",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the difference between troubleshooting and optimization.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Optimization activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 5, Level 3. Students complete the activity guide with the chatbot.",
        "progression_name": "Optimization"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c032207e-c253-4112-9b5d-01c549dde365",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17ce4a03-c166-484a-981b-6e09d1e93f12",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students going back and forth between discussing the options amongst themselves and asking the AI Chat for input. If students aren’t engaging with each other, use questioning to get them to explain their process and thinking about whichever scenario they are working through.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Optimization Activity Guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17ce4a03-c166-484a-981b-6e09d1e93f12",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fb025c63-7a06-4d38-afeb-196ddae45d4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f4a10c01-bbba-415c-b76d-44dd9bfb9430",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the Question of the Day.\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Unit Guides can be collected at the end of the lesson as a formative assessment to gauge how well students grasped the concepts of troubleshooting and optimization and which concepts might need further review."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f4a10c01-bbba-415c-b76d-44dd9bfb9430",
        "lesson_activity.key": "287928f3-c995-4568-901c-358b8d504ec7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36b0c18d-efc2-4f09-96a4-bb8d2b38bcb3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students into groups of 4.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give each student a blank piece of paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write \"Input\", \"Output\", \"Storage\", and \"Internal Components\" on separate pieces of paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students participate in a round-robin activity where they brainstorm an idea quickly, and pass their paper to the left. They start by writing one hardware example under the category heading on their paper and circle their example on the paper. They then pass their paper to the left and repeat this process, adding as many examples as possible in the time given. If a student cannot think of an example, they can skip and pass the paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As the students work, encourage them to keep coming up with examples. If a group appears stuck, encourage them to switch papers. The time will go fast, and the idea is to brainstorm as quickly as possible.\n\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This activity should be fun and fast-paced. Encourage students to write what is on their mind, even if it might not be 100% correct. They can revise and refine their contributions between rounds. There is a teacher resource available with a list of hardware suggestions to assist as needed."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36b0c18d-efc2-4f09-96a4-bb8d2b38bcb3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9c567bb8-ede9-4f3e-b397-96b3d409acf8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c73ae61b-822e-47d9-b1f7-4e6e46e538bb",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c73ae61b-822e-47d9-b1f7-4e6e46e538bb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9c567bb8-ede9-4f3e-b397-96b3d409acf8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc5c77f2-d7c2-4057-96d8-d098e67af57e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Could you make a working computer from all of the hardware that your group has listed, or are there important components missing?*\n* **Thumbs Up, Thumbs Down:** Ask a question and have students show their response with a quick thumbs-up, thumbs-down, or thumbs-sideways. Follow up by calling on a few students to explain their reasoning.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students collaboratively analyze the list of computer hardware components generated during the activity to determine if they have all the essential parts needed to build a functioning computer. They identify any missing components and explain why each component is critical to the computer's operation. This discussion aims to deepen their understanding of computer architecture and enhance their critical thinking and communication skills. If the you have time or the discussion lags, consider prompting students with this follow up question to have them examine their lists critically: Are there components listed that aren’t necessary for making a working computer?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc5c77f2-d7c2-4057-96d8-d098e67af57e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9c567bb8-ede9-4f3e-b397-96b3d409acf8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd090fd9-33e4-48f3-b553-d2e5c512f8ff",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *PC build*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Place students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Build a Computer System activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 1. Students should select a user that they want to design a computer system for and complete the User Profile section of the activity guide.",
        "progression_name": "Computer Build User Profiles"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd090fd9-33e4-48f3-b553-d2e5c512f8ff",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "072e2755-55eb-4527-b7e6-dcf339ae9d7b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 2. Students should spend a few minutes exploring PCPartPicker by clicking the blue buttons to explore different components, using the filtering options available on the left-hand side of the screen, or even exploring builds that other users have shared. ",
        "progression_name": "PCPartPicker"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "072e2755-55eb-4527-b7e6-dcf339ae9d7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6248cf93-a062-4b0a-96b1-a340f7f38a7e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Show students how to click the buttons and search components. Point out the different ways to filter - price, manufacturer, specifications, etc.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "[**PCPartPicker.com**](http://pcpartpicker.com/) is a great resource to choose components, add them in a visual UI, and to check for compatibility issues. If your students are unfamiliar, it could be helpful to demo how to navigate this site before sending students off to explore. If this website is unavailable, there are also plenty of guides on sample builds that are available online. Here are some examples:\n\n- [**Best PC builds for gaming 2025**](https://www.tomshardware.com/best-picks/best-pc-builds-gaming) from Tom's Hardware\n\n- [**Want a Better PC? Try Building Your Own**](https://www.wired.com/story/how-to-build-a-pc/) by Wired\n\n- [**How to Build a PC: The Ultimate Beginner's Guide**](https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/how-to-build-a-pc-the-ultimate-beginners-guide) by PCMag\n\n- [**The TBG DIY PC Build Guides**](https://techbuyersguru.com/tbg-diy-pc-build-guides/) by the Tech Buyer's Guru"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6248cf93-a062-4b0a-96b1-a340f7f38a7e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dde4f54a-df60-4f3a-b439-2639d0321786",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dde4f54a-df60-4f3a-b439-2639d0321786",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7491c605-1ef2-439b-b260-0b69b7a9941c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you notice about this website? What do you wonder about this website?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students might notice that this website helps users build a computer by allowing them to choose a list of compatible parts; it shows prices for different components which makes it easier to budget; there is a section for completed builds that users have shared; and there are warnings that pop up if incompatible parts are selected. Students might wonder: *What are all of the specifications for? What is the difference between brands and manufacturers? Why are some parts more expensive than others?*\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Computer Build User Profiles"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7491c605-1ef2-439b-b260-0b69b7a9941c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "04f533f1-9f82-4a3a-90e6-3fd56c6e34e2",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 6, Level 3. Students should complete their activity guide using the PCPartPicker website and the Computer Build Assistant.",
        "progression_name": "Computer Build Assistant"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "04f533f1-9f82-4a3a-90e6-3fd56c6e34e2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "643cf7a1-0fc4-47c9-bd74-f7dd97c689cb",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Assist students who are stuck, help craft questions for the AI chatbot with students, ask leading questions to get them to consider the needs of their chosen user.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Build a Computer System activity guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "643cf7a1-0fc4-47c9-bd74-f7dd97c689cb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76d2c447-ba6e-4edd-84c8-e1ef4a27554b",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76d2c447-ba6e-4edd-84c8-e1ef4a27554b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a68564b-87e3-4d32-94df-39101e49b905",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is one decision that you had to make in your build to align with your user's needs or preferences?*\n* **Turn and Talk:** Pause instruction and have students briefly discuss a question with a partner. Call on a few pairs to share insights with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share how they considered and prioritized needs and preferences while working on their build."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a68564b-87e3-4d32-94df-39101e49b905",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4078a6be-9134-44d3-a202-f9af80fef12e",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4078a6be-9134-44d3-a202-f9af80fef12e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2b83cc0b-3944-4d1d-802a-255ad6f9a8d3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b3eee94a-5f3c-4d3e-9b42-17771618efc7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b3eee94a-5f3c-4d3e-9b42-17771618efc7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "53f93b10-fa17-47f3-9713-a1ed155ab6ef"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d8a84d6c-3ea6-4b85-917e-3e0a84687a08",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *data*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a blank piece of paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Play the video clip. Students should list the data or types of data that could be collected in this scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Encourage students to think about different types of data that might be collected from the scene: \n- Visual Data - number of vehicles or pedestrians on the street\n- Audio Data - noise level, types of sounds (car horns, rain, footsteps, etc.)\n- Location Data - GPS coordinates of where the video was recorded\n- Environmental Data - Temperature, rain intensity\n- Text Data - Street signs, billboards, shop names, or license plate numbers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Students repeat the activity again for a different scene. They should write down as many ideas for how data might be gathered from the scenario that they can within a minute.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Encourage students to think about different types of data that might be collected from the scene: \n- Visual Data - Actions being performed (chopping, stirring, plating)\n- Audio Data - Type of sounds (alarms for timers, equipment hums, verbal orders)\n- Location Data - Movements of staff (areas of the kitchen frequently occupied, paths taken between stations)\n- Environmental Data - Kitchen temperature\n- Biometric Data - Stress indicators (heart rate, hurried movements)\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Students repeat the activity again for a different 10 second scene. They should write down as many ideas for how data might be gathered from the scenario that they can within a minute.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Encourage students to think about different types of data that might be collected from the scene: \n- Visual Data - Number and types of trees, plants, or rocks visible\n- Audio Data - Birdsong frequency and species identification\n- Location Data - Pathways and trails mapped within the scene\n- Environmental Data - Air quality\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Share an example of data that could be collected from one of the scenarios. Why might this data be useful?*\n* **Whip Around:** Ask a question with a short response, then go around the room quickly, having each student share one thought, idea, or answer.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students suggest ways that the data can be used. For example, in the rainy city scenario, they might suggest that the number of vehicles on the street might help city planners identify peak traffic times and design better traffic flow solutions. In the restaurant kitchen scenario, the movements of staff could help inform the kitchen layout to minimize traffic and improve workflow efficiency. In the nature scenario, the temperature or air quality could be tracked over time.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce types of data that computer systems can collect.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d8a84d6c-3ea6-4b85-917e-3e0a84687a08",
        "lesson_activity.key": "246bb482-8002-42d7-8175-8942a8affcfa"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "777276fa-6c44-494a-acdd-d7518857d7ca",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give each group a copy of the Data in Computer Systems activity guide.  \n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video  \"Intro to Sensors\" (0:17 - 1:22)\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Question to Consider While Watching:** *What might be an example of a sensor in an everyday object that you are familiar with? What data might it collect?*\n* **Think, Pair, Share:** Prompt students with a thought-provoking question and give them time to think independently. Have them discuss with a partner, then call on pairs to share key takeaways with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should realize that sensors detect or measure physical properties. Student examples will vary, but some sample responses include the auto-dimming feature of their cell phone screen (light sensor), the way that lights are turned on when you walk into a room (motion sensor), or even when your car tells you that you are almost out of gas (fuel sensor).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *sensor*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Point students to the first page in their activity guides. They will use the AI Chat in order to explore several sensors. For each, they should put the sensor name, the data type, a description of what the sensor does, and where it might be used in a computer system or device.\n\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "777276fa-6c44-494a-acdd-d7518857d7ca",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ff6b94c7-39f9-4842-a4bc-4650cb674009"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a9b181cc-b7f0-4804-af8e-3634348149a7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1. Students work on posing questions about data, sensors, and their role in a computer system.",
        "progression_name": "Sensors and AI Chatbot"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a9b181cc-b7f0-4804-af8e-3634348149a7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ff6b94c7-39f9-4842-a4bc-4650cb674009"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ebaf7898-9d35-427e-a952-4d8221aadb14",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students lay out the first page of their activity guides on their desks or tables.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students rotate around the room for 5 minutes, gathering information about sensors that their classmates explored. They should record their findings in the Unit Guide. Note: students should not feel obligated to complete the entire chart; they can always revisit and fill in additional information later. \n\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Unit Guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives:\n- Describe various types of data \n- Describe how to collect different types of data\n- Determine what types of data are needed to solve a problem\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ebaf7898-9d35-427e-a952-4d8221aadb14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ff6b94c7-39f9-4842-a4bc-4650cb674009"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5ce8d431-639b-46de-8c10-2e732acf6660",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of 3-4.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students choose one of the stations. With their group, they read the station activity card. This card sets up unique challenges or problems faced by different careers that might be solved through the use of sensors and data. Students should complete the *Empathize with the User* section of their activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students complete the *Define the Data* and *Ideate a Solution* sections of the activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** On the sticky notes at each station, students write 1 - 2 examples of data that might be collected to aid in solving the challenge or problem outlined in their scenario. They can use the sentence stems available here to help draft their response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Repeat the activity, allowing students to select a new station. Encourage them to add different data ideas to the station's sticky notes.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5ce8d431-639b-46de-8c10-2e732acf6660",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ff6b94c7-39f9-4842-a4bc-4650cb674009"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac4e3a74-dcee-4fb5-866f-070cb16fc61f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac4e3a74-dcee-4fb5-866f-070cb16fc61f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8a56c251-db56-47d1-a35d-0d90e963497e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6eef45c6-0e3b-46e9-82de-af87a96f586b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group of students 20 to 25 UNO cards.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you don't have UNO cards, there are digital card templates you can print and cut out for the activity. You can also use regular playing cards as an alternative. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6eef45c6-0e3b-46e9-82de-af87a96f586b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ee338b5-e165-4aab-ae90-57ad27ea5e88",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ee338b5-e165-4aab-ae90-57ad27ea5e88",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f8d1ba3-d49a-4cc9-ba51-424f5128904d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Your task is to sort the cards in ascending order by number. Take your time and focus on organizing your deck.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f8d1ba3-d49a-4cc9-ba51-424f5128904d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "577339de-5f2a-4bf9-a59c-27df5cb477a0",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Play the music clip (blue volume icon) during this round as students work.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Students sort their cards by number in ascending order.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss**: *What patterns or insights did you notice after sorting?*\n* **Turn and Talk:** Pause instruction and have students briefly discuss a question with a partner. Call on a few pairs to share insights with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal**: Listen for responses like, \"The cards were easier to analyze,\" or \"It helped us quickly identify the highest and lowest values.\""
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "577339de-5f2a-4bf9-a59c-27df5cb477a0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "63a85fd2-d725-436f-9b5b-d0865783ef42",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now, choose one color and filter your deck to include only the cards of that color. Set aside any cards that don't match.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "63a85fd2-d725-436f-9b5b-d0865783ef42",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "81259da4-6ec0-4dcc-a3aa-7dada9159de4",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Play the music clip (blue volume icon) during this round as students work.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Students will choose one color and filter their deck to include only the cards of that color, setting aside the others.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss**: *What patterns or insights did you notice after filtering?*\n* **Turn and Talk:** Pause instruction and have students briefly discuss a question with a partner. Call on a few pairs to share insights with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for responses like, \"We could focus on a specific group of cards,\" or \"It showed which colors had more or fewer cards.\""
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "81259da4-6ec0-4dcc-a3aa-7dada9159de4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7fbca494-fe03-4e0d-affb-ae17f30ba43b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now, count how many cards you have for each color. Record the totals for red, blue, yellow, and green.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7fbca494-fe03-4e0d-affb-ae17f30ba43b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0e7d388d-ab6a-40ed-9789-005b832f630c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Play the music clip (blue volume icon) during this round as students work.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students will count how many cards they have for each color and record the totals for red, blue, yellow, and green.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss**: *What patterns or insights did you notice after counting?*\n* **Turn and Talk:** Pause instruction and have students briefly discuss a question with a partner. Call on a few pairs to share insights with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal**: Listen for insights like, \"Red and blue cards made up most of the deck,\" or \"It helped us see which colors were more common.\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0e7d388d-ab6a-40ed-9789-005b832f630c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4f473e5a-2ecd-43ad-a4e3-704febbf9d2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d5c5429-549c-48f5-b46a-3997c471ccc8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a Processing Library Data activity guide.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Processing Library Data"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d5c5429-549c-48f5-b46a-3997c471ccc8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "75018531-ed83-43a0-8332-c1def25f40cb",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Imagine you’re a librarian who needs to make decisions quickly, like recommending books to visitors or identifying which books are rarely checked out. You can’t rely on manual sorting all the time, especially when dealing with thousands of records. That’s where computer systems and computational tasks come in. Today, we’ll work with a dataset about a library’s book collection and use computational processes to uncover patterns and make data-driven decisions, just like a computer system would. In this activity, you’ll analyze a dataset step by step, just like a computer system processes data. We’ll use a template to break the problem into clear steps. Let’s walk through an example together to get started.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "75018531-ed83-43a0-8332-c1def25f40cb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e6f1645f-1d7d-48b4-a69d-c354b6adaaaf",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition**: Direct students to open Lesson 8, Level 1. Walk students through solving the first choice level using the following steps ([here is a demo](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1tkR53BYic9eqtBFS5-Y9AAktrc_2ey-v/view) of how to do this):\n- **Define the goal:** A new visitor wants to know the hottest books to start reading.\n- **Identify the relevant data:** Popularity Score column.\n- **Choose the action (reference the action bank at the top of their activity guides):** Sort.\n- **Apply the action:** Use the spreadsheet to **sort by descending order (Z-A) of Popularity Score**.\n- **Describe the output:** The books are now listed from most popular to least popular.\n- **Reflect on insights**: This helps the library highlight the most popular books to new visitors.",
        "progression_name": "Processing Library Data"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e6f1645f-1d7d-48b4-a69d-c354b6adaaaf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f686dfc2-ac2e-4331-abef-e8eaa786b838",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**:  Model filling out the Madlib template on chart paper or the board for the first scenario: “The goal is to [show the hottest books to visitors]. The system will [Sort] the [Popularity Score column] by [descending order]. The output is [a list of books ranked by popularity] so that [visitors know the best books to start with].”"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f686dfc2-ac2e-4331-abef-e8eaa786b838",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d0c25ad1-859b-40d1-b83c-39978600a350",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Define *sort*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Define *filter*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Define *aggregate*\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d0c25ad1-859b-40d1-b83c-39978600a350",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "407c2ca9-9295-4446-80d2-71101b1baece",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now it’s your turn! Work with your partner to complete two additional library data choice levels. For each scenario, follow the steps we just practiced: define the goal, choose the action, identify the relevant data, apply the action, describe the output, and reflect on the insights.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "407c2ca9-9295-4446-80d2-71101b1baece",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "158e9d81-36ee-4ec9-b8a8-eccde169da08",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Students complete two more library data choice levels in Lesson 8, Level 1. They use their activity guide to write down the steps for two of the choice levels, and fill out the template to summarize their process and results each.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "158e9d81-36ee-4ec9-b8a8-eccde169da08",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da67ece8-ebd5-40c7-a618-33e7ea393903",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate**:\n- Observe students as they work through the scenarios.\n- Check that students are filling out their templates correctly.\n- Provide guidance or clarification if students are stuck on any step.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to think back to the UNO card activity. Remind them how sorting, filtering, and aggregating helped them see patterns and make decisions with their cards. They can apply the same strategies to the library dataset."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da67ece8-ebd5-40c7-a618-33e7ea393903",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "56fb44a0-4bfc-4a2f-9db1-a9a6026f1af3",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "56fb44a0-4bfc-4a2f-9db1-a9a6026f1af3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6db39ba8-4fc9-4572-8078-a5058cdf0a01",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Once students have completed their scenarios, lead a review as a class. \n- Ask student pairs to share their answers.\n- Highlight and clarify any differences or commonalities in their findings."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6db39ba8-4fc9-4572-8078-a5058cdf0a01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e432c14a-da34-4d68-8205-0524ccb3a4ac",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s take some time to reflect on what you’ve learned. You’ll answer three free-response questions to compare the benefits and limitations of manual and computational data processing. Think about how the tools and methods we used today improve efficiency, accuracy, and help us handle larger datasets.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Reflection",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e432c14a-da34-4d68-8205-0524ccb3a4ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f565044a-eafd-4881-a77d-908dc4f282b8",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 8, Level 2 to respond to the reflection questions on Levels 2, 3, and 4.",
        "progression_name": "Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Processing Library Data activity guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives.\n\nThe free response questions in Levels 2, 3, and 4 can be used to formatively assess the lesson objectives."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f565044a-eafd-4881-a77d-908dc4f282b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b699d64b-788b-4933-9c06-3244317f3ab4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b175c784-6ab0-45d3-8769-ee3a87102a70",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson.\n\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b175c784-6ab0-45d3-8769-ee3a87102a70",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7a8d0bfd-b94c-454c-8c54-f513b1fd10b7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f49dbeea-e896-4152-8bc9-5bd742db4470",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI helps us process large amounts of data to make predictions, from recommending what to watch on Netflix to forecasting the weather. Today, we’re going to explore how AI processes data and how the hardware behind AI impacts its performance.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f49dbeea-e896-4152-8bc9-5bd742db4470",
        "lesson_activity.key": "705e4f1d-9b38-494a-85ad-fd2713cd087d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "35ad1847-a8ad-41c1-9447-04df20385fc1",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"Can AI help us predict extreme weather\" from 0:00 to 1:39.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What types of atmospheric data gets collected by satellites, weather stations, and buoys?*\n- Round Robin Sharing: Invite students to share one data type. If time allows, go around the room or ask for volunteers.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should mention temperature, wind speed, humidity, air pressure, and cloud images as key data inputs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"Can AI help us predict extreme weather\" from 3:54 to 5:30.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What benefits are there to using AI to make weather forecasts?*\n- *Do you think AI forecasts always get it right?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** AI speeds up analysis, making predictions in seconds instead of weeks. AI models prioritize accuracy and learn from penalties for incorrect predictions. Ultimately, whether it’s done by a human or by AI it’s still a prediction or educated guess about what will happen. This particular forecasting AI prioritizes safer, more likely outcomes and can miss catastrophic weather events. This is especially true because these AI models are trained on the past 40 years of weather data and we currently have (and will continue to have) more unpredictable, extreme weather events due to climate change.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "35ad1847-a8ad-41c1-9447-04df20385fc1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "705e4f1d-9b38-494a-85ad-fd2713cd087d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bce64e0b-085d-4a3f-a866-fd2f629a8bf1",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": " <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define *processing unit*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Explain that just like different tools are suited for different jobs, AI models need the right kind of hardware to function efficiently. Computers use different types of processing units depending on the task. Some are more flexible, meaning they can handle a variety of tasks, while others are built for efficiency, meaning they are designed for a specific purpose and run faster with less energy. Let’s explore how these four processing units work.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Click through the animated slide to introduce CPUs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Click through the animated slide to introduce GPUs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Click through the animated slide to introduce FPGA.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Click through the animated slide to introduce ASICs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to open Lesson 9, Level 1. Students will select a computing task from a list of options and choose a processing unit (CPU, GPU, FPGA, or ASIC) to complete the task. They will observe the benchmarking results and receive a performance score based on their selection. Students should record their observations in their activity guide, analyzing which processor performed best for each task and why.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "AI Hardware",
        "progression_name": "Processing Unit Battle"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bce64e0b-085d-4a3f-a866-fd2f629a8bf1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1c12a16-61e4-47b3-ba50-05ee9a69f2c1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "efbb3c8d-a277-4b2b-b614-d6c7187e2d0f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a How AI Uses Data activity guide.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "AI in the Real World"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "efbb3c8d-a277-4b2b-b614-d6c7187e2d0f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1c12a16-61e4-47b3-ba50-05ee9a69f2c1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "817237d5-d4e7-440d-ad0f-66702d85a91e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "AI systems use data to make decisions in real-world applications. Let’s explore how different AI models function and what data they rely on.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "817237d5-d4e7-440d-ad0f-66702d85a91e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1c12a16-61e4-47b3-ba50-05ee9a69f2c1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fb7efed-151d-43bb-bcdb-2c477275d582",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students into groups of 3-4. Assign each group an AI use case:\n- Voice Assistants (Alexa/Siri): AI processes voice input and generates responses.\n- Self-Driving Cars: AI uses sensor data to navigate roads.\n- Medical Imaging AI: AI scans medical images for disease detection.\n- AI Translation Tools: AI converts text/audio between languages.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to open Lesson 9, Level 2. In their groups, students will watch a video about the assigned technology and answer the following questions in their activity guide:\n- What is the AI model doing in this scenario?\n- What type of data is being input?\n- What is the decision being made? In other words, what does this AI system do with the data?\n- Why does this task require speed and scale?",
        "progression_name": "Explore an AI Model"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fb7efed-151d-43bb-bcdb-2c477275d582",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1c12a16-61e4-47b3-ba50-05ee9a69f2c1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9581d646-fb04-451f-b2b2-9e071e3c2e5a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Make sure that all students are able to answer all questions. At the end of the lesson, students will do a jigsaw activity to share out their answers."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9581d646-fb04-451f-b2b2-9e071e3c2e5a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1c12a16-61e4-47b3-ba50-05ee9a69f2c1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe212366-5fe4-4f96-8f9f-8a30fba5ba5f",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This**: Direct students to Lesson 9, Level 3. Students use AI Chat to research and choose the best AI hardware for various tasks that might be associated with an AI model",
        "progression_name": "Determine AI Hardware",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The How AI Uses Data Activity Guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe212366-5fe4-4f96-8f9f-8a30fba5ba5f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1c12a16-61e4-47b3-ba50-05ee9a69f2c1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc3e3323-0bc1-46b4-9d9d-ed0de4940d2b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson.\n\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc3e3323-0bc1-46b4-9d9d-ed0de4940d2b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1912e6f-02ae-4b2f-b9d3-b6b668821931"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ccc7c67b-199f-4366-b55d-10dfde3d739c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Form new groups (1 student from each AI case study per group). Each student presents their AI system, explaining what the AI model does, what kind of data it processes, and what hardware best supports it and why.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate**: Ensure students explain why specific hardware is best suited for their AI model.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to compare AI hardware choices in terms of speed, power consumption, and cost. Real-world constraints, such as affordability and energy efficiency, often determine the best hardware for an AI task."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ccc7c67b-199f-4366-b55d-10dfde3d739c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a1912e6f-02ae-4b2f-b9d3-b6b668821931"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "707d43e2-ded8-43bf-af0a-a0c095ca37b9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Play the video (0:00 - 1:48).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some other examples of IoT devices you've heard about or used?*\n* **Sticky Note Swap:** Have students write a response on a sticky note, then trade notes with a partner. They read and respond to their partner’s idea before sharing key insights with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Get students to realize they interact with IoT devices and systems in different parts of their lives. For example, a smartwatch tracks your steps and sends the information to an app on your phone, or a smart thermostat adjusts the temperature in your home based on the weather outside.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Videos are used throughout the curriculum to spark discussions, supplement key concepts with additional explanations and examples, and expose students to the various roles and backgrounds of individuals in computer science.\n\nWhile interacting with the video, turn on closed captioning so students can also read along as they watch.\n\nTo encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "707d43e2-ded8-43bf-af0a-a0c095ca37b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "287f44cf-422f-4f21-b448-8ed18fcf4181"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "60e6ce83-0494-433c-818d-cd7ea05dfa22",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "60e6ce83-0494-433c-818d-cd7ea05dfa22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "287f44cf-422f-4f21-b448-8ed18fcf4181"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f8922409-7272-4fd5-aaed-68519657a4cd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *Internet of Things (IoT)*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f8922409-7272-4fd5-aaed-68519657a4cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "287f44cf-422f-4f21-b448-8ed18fcf4181"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1f9b2fc0-f4c6-4543-a75f-377d7663168f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of The Internet of Things activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce examples of standalone devices, such as pedometers or digital thermometers. Then give students examples of IoT devices, such as an Alexa speaker or a Ring camera.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to choose one pair of devices and respond to the first question on the activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are different ways that you might connect a device in order to communicate data?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This should be a quick whole-class discussion to activate prior knowledge before reviewing some of the different methods that IoT devices communicate to the internet.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Exploring IoT Systems, Hardware, and Privacy Concerns"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1f9b2fc0-f4c6-4543-a75f-377d7663168f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "62711ee8-222b-4c2d-b588-4d6a97dd1e40"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fff9100-f534-4540-b9ac-0e39ee31bcf4",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Once a device has data, it must be transmitted in some fashion to be processed. One way to determine what transmission system is best for a given IoT device is to gauge the range that the data needs to travel.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fff9100-f534-4540-b9ac-0e39ee31bcf4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "62711ee8-222b-4c2d-b588-4d6a97dd1e40"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "89b1bfc5-a779-41db-82cb-c2ecc721569b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Introduce the examples for short-range communications.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students complete the corresponding section of their unit guide. For each of the examples presented, have students brainstorm a device or two that uses that communication protocol.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the examples for short-range communications. Have students complete the corresponding section of their unit guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the examples for medium-range communications. Have students complete the corresponding section of their unit guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the examples for long-range communications. Have students complete the corresponding section of their unit guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the examples for long-range communications. Have students complete the corresponding section of their unit guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to finish the remaining two questions on their activity guide:\n- How might the device transmit data, if at all?\n- What privacy risks might this device introduce?\n- With internet connectivity, how might a device’s functionality change?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 10, Level 1 to respond to the question.",
        "progression_name": "Security, Privacy, and Data Ownership",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This level can be used to assess students' ability to analyze the privacy and ethical implications of IoT systems."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "89b1bfc5-a779-41db-82cb-c2ecc721569b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "62711ee8-222b-4c2d-b588-4d6a97dd1e40"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9be67555-12be-494a-b993-2b68c35d55b8",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9be67555-12be-494a-b993-2b68c35d55b8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "62711ee8-222b-4c2d-b588-4d6a97dd1e40"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "21c9ca81-7ad5-45cc-9686-ae3d2477f7d8",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Have each student make a copy of the Smart Classroom Template.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Design a Smart Classroom activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the steps students need to take to complete the activity. Refer to the example that is in the template.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students participate in a Give One, Get One to share the innovation they developed. Students should share the innovation as well as the data it collects, how it transmits that information, and any privacy or security concerns that might exist.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Design a Smart Classroom",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "During a Give One, Get One activity, students should wander the classroom while the music is playing, find a partner, share their smart classroom innovation, and listen to the innovation proposed by their partner. While the music is still playing, students should repeat the exercise with a new partner. If there is extra time, possible differentiations for this activity include giving one piece of feedback to their partner, and leading the activity into a class discussion where some students share a refined version of their idea with the class based on partner discussion and feedback."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Smart Classroom activity can be used to assess students' understanding of various types of IoT systems, the hardware needed for these systems, and their applications in real-world contexts."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "21c9ca81-7ad5-45cc-9686-ae3d2477f7d8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "62711ee8-222b-4c2d-b588-4d6a97dd1e40"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "895f046f-06f4-41f1-a590-ddbcb01aa365",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson.\n\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "895f046f-06f4-41f1-a590-ddbcb01aa365",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2f9365a7-e115-4d6a-92ab-7e7ca348b57b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b72bc9b8-4e1f-4f31-b649-8c4c6e92d2ad",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video \"Guerilla Testing with Usability Cafe\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> Questions to Consider with the **Video:** *How might usability testing look different when testing a physical device or system that is not run solely on a computer, tablet, or phone?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to bring up challenges when testing something that has many parts and might need to be done in specific environments and/or under specific circumstances.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b72bc9b8-4e1f-4f31-b649-8c4c6e92d2ad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6d1202c-d6ab-4611-866d-1e4bcbd4b01d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9291227c-33c7-482c-96b5-4405fc03ebd5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9291227c-33c7-482c-96b5-4405fc03ebd5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6d1202c-d6ab-4611-866d-1e4bcbd4b01d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "45b6bb0d-1bc6-4d7b-9f74-c9b4f171b56d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define *user testing*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "45b6bb0d-1bc6-4d7b-9f74-c9b4f171b56d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a6d1202c-d6ab-4611-866d-1e4bcbd4b01d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26c4aada-2f63-43bb-8578-5239c079fb48",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 1. Students look at user testing results for a product and pull out the main themes.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "User Testing Data",
        "progression_name": "User Testing Results"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26c4aada-2f63-43bb-8578-5239c079fb48",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43642c64-e695-46cd-9369-9aaa95282480",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Walk around to ensure students are looking at all the types of data (observations, user survey response tables, and feedback) when doing their analysis."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43642c64-e695-46cd-9369-9aaa95282480",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a994ba0-28dc-41db-bd0c-37f469b0b3ee",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 2 to work with the chatbot to help summarize the same data they just looked at.",
        "progression_name": "Using AI to Analyze Data"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a994ba0-28dc-41db-bd0c-37f469b0b3ee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9029874b-5298-4a84-9ee1-d6967ef5629b",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How is AI helpful when processing user testing data? What would have been difficult to do without it?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to point out for when the chatbot noticed something that they did not or for times when AI summarized the results more clearly. Also make sure to make space in the conversation for evaluating the AI responses and having students share the tips they used to help the AI work better at generating insights from the data or when the AI made incorrect statements from the data.\n\nDepending on where the discussion goes, here are some potential follow-up questions to engage the class with:\n- Which summary do you think you would include a report to the team working on this product, yours or the chatbots? Why?\n- How do you think your summary would have been different if you’d used AI to summarize the data first before doing your own analysis?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9029874b-5298-4a84-9ee1-d6967ef5629b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f65f099-8a35-4df7-87d2-ce1cab6a160d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have a student read the scenario out loud.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 3. Students will see the same scenario, along with four choices for how Alice should respond to this situation.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "What's Next",
        "progression_name": "Alice's Scenario"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f65f099-8a35-4df7-87d2-ce1cab6a160d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "84920533-95e2-42be-af2e-75427ccce4a5",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they decide which option they think Alice should pick. When students have made a decision, the background of the app will turn green. When most students have green screens, return to the front of the room and use the “View Student Responses” button to project the class responses to the room. This graph can be used for the discussion on the next slide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This level is designed to use the Student Summaries feature, which lets you view and display the responses from the class. This requires having this level opened on your computer and, in the teacher panel, selecting the current section of your classes. [**Click here to learn more about viewing student responses**](https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/14544890300301-Can-I-see-a-summary-of-all-my-students-responses-for-question-based-levels). If you are unable to use the student summaries, you can also run this as an unplugged discussion where students vote in their seats or move to different corners of the room depending on their responses. Ultimately, students need a way to take a stand and be ready to discuss their opinions in the next slide."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "84920533-95e2-42be-af2e-75427ccce4a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b28ec7f0-c411-4429-b4d8-04e816ed5a85",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b28ec7f0-c411-4429-b4d8-04e816ed5a85",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5743d98f-921b-4a77-9652-8aac47413b34",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  *Who should Alice prioritize in her design decisions, and how might her choice affect the product’s purpose and impact?*\n- Use the information from the student summary screen (or other class voting method) to guide the conversation. Invite a student from each area to share their rationale.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** There is no definitive right answer here, as long as students can explain and justify their thoughts. Some students may choose option A, given that the device works as intended for the specific target user – gamers with mobility issues. Other students may gravitate towards options B or C - either fixing it after launch, or delaying in order to fix - because it doesn’t work as well as it should for all users and it should be made more equitable before launching.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Regardless of what answer students pick, the more important goal is for students to recognize that there are still important decisions - made by humans - before their technology should be released to the public, and this exercise introduces students to some of the choices they could make. Additionally, students should discuss who to prioritize when making updates. In this case, should they prioritize the positive feedback they received from mobility challenged gamers (primary user) or from other gamers (secondary users)?"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5743d98f-921b-4a77-9652-8aac47413b34",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8ac1216c-e7ad-41ae-a0c1-0bddcb5905a3",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8ac1216c-e7ad-41ae-a0c1-0bddcb5905a3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "495f8ea5-f9d4-4002-a151-b73c5e05849b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have a student read the scenario out loud.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 4. Students will see the same scenario, along with four choices for how Josh should respond to this situation.",
        "progression_name": "Josh's Scenario"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "495f8ea5-f9d4-4002-a151-b73c5e05849b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fdc38080-1264-4d90-bc88-6a3e4a8aaea0",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they decide which option they think Josh should pick. When students have made a decision, the background of the app will turn green. When most students have green screens, return to the front of the room and use the “View Student Responses” button to project the class responses to the room. This graph can be used for the discussion on the next slide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fdc38080-1264-4d90-bc88-6a3e4a8aaea0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "08a8c255-d813-4b90-b3f0-ba06bb5c341a",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are the risks of releasing a product that works better for some groups than others, and how could Josh design more fairly for all users?*\n- Use the information from the student summary screen (or other class voting method) to guide the conversation. Invite a student from each area to share their rationale.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This answer tends to have a more moral or ethical component, since the technology shows a clear gender bias against women, who are more likely to have higher pitched voices and therefore not be able to use the technology. Students will likely gravitate towards options C or D, opting to cancel or pause implementation so more testing can be conducted and the harm can be addressed before it is released.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This scenario is based on real-world events where this exact situation unfolded - multiple car companies released voice activated phone systems knowing that they were unlikely to work for women -you can read more about that here. The real-life version of this may be surprising to students - the companies initially ignored the user testing feedback and went with option (B), releasing the voice-recognition system to the public first before making changes. It was only after several years that these harmful effects were addressed. You can decide if you want to highlight this scenario with students and discuss the approach to user testing: “Improvements were made first for males, then females, then Midwestern speakers. Finally it was adjusted for Southern speakers and people from New England.”"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "08a8c255-d813-4b90-b3f0-ba06bb5c341a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4dfda98f-8ec5-430f-97a7-62f9acc6becc",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4dfda98f-8ec5-430f-97a7-62f9acc6becc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a6d9bf1-6fad-4d9b-9e5f-84d7601edc7a",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have a student read the scenario out loud.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Lesson 11, Level 5. Here is another scenario where students can explore and discuss how to respond. The scenario is also provided on the next slide.",
        "progression_name": "Lydia's Scenario"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a6d9bf1-6fad-4d9b-9e5f-84d7601edc7a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d5fecfae-a529-41f5-b8d3-a6af58a36653",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Monitor students as they decide which option to pick. When students have made a decision, the background of the app will turn green. When most students have green screens, return to the front of the room and use the “View Student Responses” button to project the class responses to the room. This graph can be used for the discussion on the next slide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d5fecfae-a529-41f5-b8d3-a6af58a36653",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f2abf42-fa11-48b4-ab3f-4dcd7fbace14",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How can Lydia redesign her product so that all users, including those who are color blind, can understand its signals clearly?*\n- Use the information from the student summary screen (or other class voting method) to guide the conversation. Invite a student from each area to share their rationale.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Help students understand that people experience technology differently, and that good design includes options that work for everyone—not just most people.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Give one example of something you heard a classmate share that made you think about one of the scenarios differently.*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students noting when someone shared something from a different perspective. You may need to push students to explore this part a bit more, but the goal here is for them to understand the collaborative decision making with a group of people who bring different perspectives leads to better outcomes.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The User Testing activity guide can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives:\n- Explain why user testing is an important part of the development process\n- Justify next steps for a product based on user testing insights and diverse perspectives\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f2abf42-fa11-48b4-ab3f-4dcd7fbace14",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9de60d95-fd0a-4a9f-bd67-0bf8272256b4",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9de60d95-fd0a-4a9f-bd67-0bf8272256b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "050a579c-4ddc-40b3-909d-0961e40af842"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f125f8db-96c2-4aa4-807b-72b1b17d4a24",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f125f8db-96c2-4aa4-807b-72b1b17d4a24",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5b45d7f0-bd4b-42ec-b4ff-fae765f890e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8eb1c3f2-1bbc-489e-b7ac-5de4f12a2b04",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Based on their Question of the Day reflection, have students write down their top two reasons why user testing can improve a product in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write down their top two answers for what happens when user testing is skipped in their unit guides.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you choose, and why?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to cite examples shared during the class period and/or personal experiences the students have had themselves as justifications for their answers.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8eb1c3f2-1bbc-489e-b7ac-5de4f12a2b04",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5b45d7f0-bd4b-42ec-b4ff-fae765f890e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "422fc75d-d5b9-4e35-a37f-844c5caf1faa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video \"Ethics and AI: Privacy and the Future of Work\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Prompt students to consider the questions posed here as they watch the video.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "422fc75d-d5b9-4e35-a37f-844c5caf1faa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a38e56a8-c378-4ce5-80ce-9721b5491aa1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "820d25ca-f60f-4962-946a-f8eac14cea94",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "820d25ca-f60f-4962-946a-f8eac14cea94",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a38e56a8-c378-4ce5-80ce-9721b5491aa1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "354c0a71-361c-4d5f-99f5-5c426bd2f694",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What computer system in the video might raise ethical concerns for some people? What are those concerns?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Guide students to recognize that artificial intelligence and robotics—particularly systems designed to collect personal data or replace human workers—can raise ethical concerns regarding privacy, job displacement, and the broader social impact of technology. Encourage them to explore how these concerns might differ among various stakeholders and emphasize the importance of transparency, responsible data handling, and dignity in AI-driven solutions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "354c0a71-361c-4d5f-99f5-5c426bd2f694",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a38e56a8-c378-4ce5-80ce-9721b5491aa1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "95adcaf8-4b3e-4636-9bab-58d4709a7745",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Put students into groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group access to their own copy of the slide template.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Define *ethics*.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Student should access a class-editable version of the Slide template. Each member of the group should pick a distinct stakeholder– there are four stakeholder per scenario.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Students should populate the digital sticky notes on the slide that corresponds to the scenario and stakeholder that they are examining. There are a variety of different discussion questions that the students can choose to answer with their group.",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Exploration",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "The students' goal is to think and respond from the perspective of the stakeholder which they are assigned—considering their concerns, responsibilities, and priorities. As students think about their stakeholder’s perspective, they can use the information provided to consider:\n- What does this stakeholder’ value most in this situation?\n- What pressures or responsibilities influence their decisions?\n- How might they react to different arguments from other stakeholders?\n- What personal experiences, beliefs, or priorities might shape their viewpoint?\n\nEven if students don’t personally agree with the stakeholder’s stance, encourage them to try to empathize and to defend their position as convincingly as possible. The goal isn’t to win a debate—it’s to deeply understand different perspectives on ethics, privacy, and technology in education."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "95adcaf8-4b3e-4636-9bab-58d4709a7745",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c731843b-b54c-4934-aaf2-73679676f8f8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c731843b-b54c-4934-aaf2-73679676f8f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "961c946f-d7b3-48c6-8138-705ee9e7e630",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Remind students that their proposal should reflect a compromise between stakeholders, not just one perspective. Encourage students to justify their ideas and challenge each other’s assumptions respectfully.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have groups present their proposals and discuss differences in approaches.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "**Push for Consensus:** If groups struggle to agree, prompt them to identify common ground or adjust their proposal to better address concerns. Ask groups to consider whose interests are best served by their proposal and who might still have concerns."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "961c946f-d7b3-48c6-8138-705ee9e7e630",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1479c937-e388-443d-8030-b405e9342752",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students repeat this process for one of the remaining scenarios. They can refer to the slide to remind them of the high level steps they need to go through.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The slides can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives:\n- Evaluate the ethical implications of real-world examples of emerging technologies, including those that incorporate AI.\n- Develop ethical guidelines for the responsible design and development of AI and emerging technologies.\n"
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There are two additional scenarios is the template. You may choose to assign groups to scenarios or let them self-select, based on what best matches with your classroom culture. If time allows, you may choose to have groups pair up and share their proposals once they are done with the second scenario."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1479c937-e388-443d-8030-b405e9342752",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8505c9e8-62fb-4872-a032-c15a9d4393f3",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Share an insight or highlight from your group's exploration of this issue in AI Ethics.*\n* **Numbered Heads Together:** Assign students numbers in small groups and give them a discussion prompt. After a short discussion, randomly call out a number—students with that number share their group’s response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal with this discussion is to allow students to share their learning and ethical explorations with the class, and to talk through their personal thoughts about the ethical considerations of the scenario apart from the stakeholder that had been assigned.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Student guidelines could address fairness, transparency, privacy, or another important ethical concern. Example: \"AI systems should be transparent about how they make decisions to ensure accountability.\""
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The ethical guidelines can be collected and used to formatively assess the lesson objectives:\n- Develop ethical guidelines for the responsible design and development of AI and emerging technologies.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8505c9e8-62fb-4872-a032-c15a9d4393f3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5632a0da-5c0d-491b-8fe2-8f21773f8dbe",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Ethical Guideline Activity Guide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "AI Guidelines"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5632a0da-5c0d-491b-8fe2-8f21773f8dbe",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "156055eb-0290-424e-8cfe-a9cfd800726a",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Based on your discussion, students should identify a key ethical value or rule that should guide the responsible use of technology. They should write this on a half-sheet of paper."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "156055eb-0290-424e-8cfe-a9cfd800726a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "86ffa535-2413-400d-9080-3a253733e9d1",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students fold their activity guides in half along the dotted line and hang up the ethical guidelines that they have developed around the classroom or in the hallway. They should wander around and read what other classmates have written as a result of their learning and conversations.\n",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You can have students vote for their top three ethical guidelines – by having them write a plus or star on the ethical guideline, or with the use of stickers. This can lead to an interesting conversation in which the top three guidelines are reviewed and discussed as a class."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "86ffa535-2413-400d-9080-3a253733e9d1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3aae3ba4-7743-4e6b-b57b-586791d98497",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3aae3ba4-7743-4e6b-b57b-586791d98497",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ce5cf158-4776-4bed-832d-f5e232708a2d",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Lesson 12, Level 1 to respond to the question.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ce5cf158-4776-4bed-832d-f5e232708a2d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "08f0cc26-2c24-43db-8322-c7ea9e361e52"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac60c6ba-a164-45dc-91af-2d5ecad9f28b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their AI and the Systems That Power It Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac60c6ba-a164-45dc-91af-2d5ecad9f28b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a9754dfb-d9fc-4cfe-a1a3-eb68b869ac2f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f127f549-c70d-402a-86a6-56698896c7cd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students into groups of two or three for the project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a Sustainable Systems project guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain to students that you will be starting a three day project today centered around designing a computer system that helps make the world a better place. Introduce the UN Sustainable Development Goals as the specific framework that students will be using to pick a focus for their project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video \"UN Sustainable Development Goals\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Question To Consider While Watching:** *Which goals are personally relevant or interesting to you?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for students to be making connections to their lives, communities, friends, and family as they talk about which goals are of interest to them.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To encourage active engagement and reflection, use one or more of the strategies discussed in the [**Guide to Curriculum Videos**](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Y-kGl_pc2afuSBKhKkdulu53X50mc7T-RQZA4vGLpY4/edit?usp=sharing)."
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you want to spend more time introducing your class to these goals, this [**TED Talk by Michael Greene**](https://youtu.be/o08ykAqLOxk?si=bLEBRBAzzs1pbcp7) goes into much more detail about them."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f127f549-c70d-402a-86a6-56698896c7cd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "543ad096-4021-4286-afa5-cf470089d2f8",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "543ad096-4021-4286-afa5-cf470089d2f8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26544f76-00b6-44cd-a26b-e82f646e6222",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to read the rubric on pages 8-9 and look at the example project on pages 10-11 of the Sustainable Systems project guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Show students the example of what a completed system diagram project might look like using the slide with the blown up version of the system diagram. Point out that this example project was done in line with Target 12.5 - “By 2030, substantially reduce waste generation through prevention, reduction, recycling and reuse”. Give students time to look over the rubric and the example project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What do you notice about the rubric and example project? What do you wonder about the rubric and example project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements, rubric, and example project."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26544f76-00b6-44cd-a26b-e82f646e6222",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8ef08c6e-1466-4fa2-9e5c-65956384f9a9",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 1 to look through the different categories of targets and list the ones they are interested in under Explore SDG Targets in their Project Guide. Once they have listed the targets they are individually interested in, have them discuss with their groups and pick one target to focus their project on.",
        "duration": "25",
        "name": "Activity",
        "progression_name": "Explore Sustainable Development Goal Targets"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8ef08c6e-1466-4fa2-9e5c-65956384f9a9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "83af076d-6308-46f8-b747-e729a6222c3c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students use discuss the targets they identified as interesting and get them to agree on one target to focus on for their project. Direct students to record this target in their Project Guide under Select an SDG Target.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 2 to use AI Chat to help them learn more about the target they’ve chosen and start to brainstorm potential solutions and project ideas.",
        "progression_name": "Brainstorm Your Project",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Open Lesson 13 Level 2 and model for students how to use AI Chat in the brainstorming process. Demonstrate an example conversation where AI helps brainstorm ideas. Some questions to try: \n- How could technology help solve the effects of natural disasters?\n- What kinds of sensors or data could be used to address pollution?\n- How might a computer system (hardware, software, network) be designed to improve energy efficiency?\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "83af076d-6308-46f8-b747-e729a6222c3c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f900bca-3baf-431c-b40d-bf21bcc83eb5",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Brainstorm Your Project"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f900bca-3baf-431c-b40d-bf21bcc83eb5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4dc3f604-2d63-4193-afcb-22e9140cfca6",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students discuss their project ideas with their group and agree on one idea to design for their project. Students should wrote a description of the system in the Project Description section of their project guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Discussing project ideas with the group is part of the **Understand** step of the **UMPIRE** strategy. It helps students ensure they have a strong foundation from which to make their plan."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4dc3f604-2d63-4193-afcb-22e9140cfca6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11b11abc-15ac-4652-914b-1aad1a32e576",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 3 to use AI Chat to help them empathize with users.",
        "progression_name": "Understanding Your Users",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students who are excited about their ideas may want to rush past this part to get to the prototyping and designing of the device. Remind them about the importance in going slow and considering diverse perspectives from the start of the design process to ensure less need for reworking and revising designs later in the process."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11b11abc-15ac-4652-914b-1aad1a32e576",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7de51764-b449-437b-8a5b-25ab348e3241",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to work in their groups to complete Rapid Prototype section in their Project Guides which includes defining the data that might be needed and sketching a rapid prototype.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Push students to not fret over details at this point as the goal of the first day is to get ideas flowing and to quickly put pen to paper so groups can get an idea of what components their device will need to solve the problem it is designed to solve.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Creating this diagram is part of the **Produce** step of the **UMPIRE** strategy. Help students to see this process as something cyclical where they may repeat steps over the course of a project. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7de51764-b449-437b-8a5b-25ab348e3241",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f6291a2c-5856-4174-aeb4-6ed5b9f61f6f",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to complete the components section in their project guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are discussing and sharing these reflection questions with a thought partner.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "progression_name": "Survey",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If time permits, have students share their thoughts and ideas with a neighbor and with the class. This sharing is part of the **Inspect** step of the **UMPIRE** strategy. By sharing and hearing from others, students will be set up to iterate on their project the following day. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f6291a2c-5856-4174-aeb4-6ed5b9f61f6f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b5ce20af-fdf0-414e-a8f8-fb0d5a960978"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "61679b14-4fb3-4617-b7ef-12169e037b68",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to complete Step 3 Data Flow in their project guide with the help of their group.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are discussing and sharing ideas with their group members. If groups come up with more than one answer for these, remind them that their system can use multiple types of data to help solve the problem.",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Working through the Data Flow is part of the **Make a Plan** step of the **UMPIRE** strategy. Hopefully students took some ideas away from the first day of their work on this project they can incorporate into this planning stage."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "61679b14-4fb3-4617-b7ef-12169e037b68",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f2c210e-1962-467e-a672-c6bdd4c8a36b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11394926-4ab3-432e-baf9-ba134197a12f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each group of students a copy of the System Diagram slides template and a System Diagram Checklist.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write a problem statement in the Problem Statement section of their project guide. Students should add this to their system diagram.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to work collaboratively on the System Diagram, starting with the system description and then moving on to building the diagram from the library of components provided and the template items provided.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure that groups are dividing up work and collaborating on the different parts of building this diagram, discussing issues and questions as they arise.",
        "duration": "35",
        "name": "Activity",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Creating the diagram is part of the **Produce** step of the **UMPIRE** strategy. Help students remember that a project that meets the guidelines should be the priority over making the “perfect” project."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11394926-4ab3-432e-baf9-ba134197a12f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f2c210e-1962-467e-a672-c6bdd4c8a36b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "21d6645b-5996-4c04-907a-f514c4409997",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to complete the Day 2 Reflection section in their project guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are discussing and sharing these reflection questions with a thought partner.\n\n**Teaching Tip**If time permits, have students share their thoughts and ideas with a neighbor and with the class.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "21d6645b-5996-4c04-907a-f514c4409997",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7f2c210e-1962-467e-a672-c6bdd4c8a36b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8995b21d-49fa-466c-848d-bd94edce691f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is one feature of your project that you think will impress others?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Give students a chance to share about the things they feel good about from their project heading into the gallery walk where they will be showing their work to others.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8995b21d-49fa-466c-848d-bd94edce691f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0015659c-9f51-4fd6-97c2-9206b880736d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ad251212-a45d-412d-9bae-0eb7266242c3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have groups get their presentations ready for the gallery walk and set them up around the room so that there is space to move smoothly around the room and gather at each station.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the questions for students to consider when looking at each system diagram. Provide each student with some post-it notes and have them write responses to the questions and leave them in the area of the presentation before moving on to the next diagram.",
        "duration": "35",
        "name": "Activity",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Before starting, set clear expectations: students will analyze projects, provide feedback, and rotate through stations. Walk through the first visit together to model reading the diagram, identifying hardware/software components, connecting to SDGs, and discussing ethical considerations. Use a structured feedback approach and keep rotations timed and organized.\n\nModel the process for the first visit (observe, analyze, discuss). Use a simple feedback framework:\n- I notice… (Observation)\n- I wonder… (Question)\n- Some ethical issues that might arise are… (Ethics)\n\nSet time limits (e.g., four to six minutes per station) and use a visual timer.\n\nGive a 1-minute warning before rotations and remind students to make sure they’ve left post-it notes by the station."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ad251212-a45d-412d-9bae-0eb7266242c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0015659c-9f51-4fd6-97c2-9206b880736d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "21cee7c7-6e5b-4579-8e24-220ebb67537e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "21cee7c7-6e5b-4579-8e24-220ebb67537e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0015659c-9f51-4fd6-97c2-9206b880736d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a0c447ab-b8f6-4ec2-b08d-040496dd2d7c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 4. Students use the chatbot to help synthesize this feedback and uncover any areas related to ethics and societal impact they hadn’t already thought of.\n",
        "progression_name": "Ethics and Impact"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a0c447ab-b8f6-4ec2-b08d-040496dd2d7c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0015659c-9f51-4fd6-97c2-9206b880736d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3035aeb1-da4d-402d-b756-52725babdff9",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 13, Level 5. Students will upload their computer system diagram into the AI Chat in order to receive feedback on how to improve it. ",
        "progression_name": "Computer System Diagram Feedback"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3035aeb1-da4d-402d-b756-52725babdff9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0015659c-9f51-4fd6-97c2-9206b880736d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "295722e9-82e2-4c63-949a-09fc06a3935b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to use the remaining time in class to complete the reflection section of their diagram and to make any improvements or revisions to their project they think will help them align better with the criteria on the rubric.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students submit their projects before the end of class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Reflecting at the end of the project is part of the **Explain** step of the **UMPIRE** strategy. It helps students synthesize the experience and walk away with lessons learned. "
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use the Sustainable Systems Project Rubric to assess students."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "295722e9-82e2-4c63-949a-09fc06a3935b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0015659c-9f51-4fd6-97c2-9206b880736d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "01109e2a-c3a7-49ce-9da4-ebc5042e8c5e",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Click the animated slide to display the discussion prompts.*\n- *What did you learn about yourself as a designer or problem solver during this project?* \n- *What did you learn about designing ethical and sustainable systems?* \n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This wrap-up gives students a chance to reflect on their learning journey — not just their final product. It helps them connect their work to their growth as a designer, thinker, or team member, and reflect on how their understanding of ethical and sustainable design evolved throughout the project.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "01109e2a-c3a7-49ce-9da4-ebc5042e8c5e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0015659c-9f51-4fd6-97c2-9206b880736d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f7c09a6-a7d6-4086-8e14-b1c9ad3bb6b4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "After completing this project, students should complete the End of Unit Survey linked in the final level. Their responses help us understand their experiences and improve future versions of this unit.",
        "progression_name": "End of Unit Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f7c09a6-a7d6-4086-8e14-b1c9ad3bb6b4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3178859e-e41f-40aa-85d4-7fa78a0a3983"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ee929669-dca3-40b3-926f-efa185b2f706",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "End of Unit Assessment"
      },
